\b\fs34 \cf0 1990s\
\pard\pardeftab720\sl380\sa120

\b0\fs26 \cf0 An early attempt at media recognition was his quest to be the first surfer to complete a 360 degree loop while strapped to his board. The attempt was chronicled in Greg Stump's 1990 ski film, 
\i Groove - Requiem in the key of Ski
\i0 . In the early 1990s, Hamilton, along with a small group of friends collectively dubbed the "Strapped Crew" because their feet were strapped to their boards, pushed the boundaries of surfing at {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Jaws_surf_break"}}{\fldrslt \cf3 Jaws surf break}} off the north central coast of {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Maui"}}{\fldrslt \cf3 Maui}}. The Strapped Crew tackled bigger waves featuring stunts. Stunts included: launching 30-foot (9.1\'a0m) jumps on sailboards, then mating the boards to paragliders to experiment with some of the earliest kiteboards.{\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Laird_Hamilton#cite_note-8"}}{\fldrslt 
\fs22 \cf3 [8]}}\
In late 1992, Hamilton with two of his close friends, big wave riders {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Darrick_Doerner"}}{\fldrslt \cf3 Darrick Doerner}} and {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "http://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=Buzzy_Kerbox&action=edit&redlink=1"}}{\fldrslt \cf6 Buzzy Kerbox}} (also an occasional men's fashion model; Hamilton and Kerbox later lost their friendship over a property disagreement),{\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Laird_Hamilton#cite_note-deadmens-3"}}{\fldrslt 
\fs22 \cf3 [3]}} started using inflatable boats to tow one another into waves which were too big to catch under paddle power alone. This innovation is chronicled in the documentary film, {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Riding_Giants"}}{\fldrslt 
\i \cf3 Riding Giants}}.{\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Laird_Hamilton#cite_note-giants-4"}}{\fldrslt 
\fs22 \cf3 [4]}} The technique would later be modified to use {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Personal_water_craft"}}{\fldrslt \cf3 personal water craft}} and become a popular innovation. {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Tow-in_surfing"}}{\fldrslt \cf3 Tow-in surfing}}, as it became known, pushed the confinements and possibilities of big wave surfing to a new level. Although met with mixed reactions from the surfing community, some of whom felt that it was cheating and polluting, Hamilton explained that tow-in surfing was the only way to catch the monstrous sized waves. Using tow-in surfing methods, Hamilton learned how to survive 70-foot (21\'a0m) waves and carving arcs across walls of water.
