\fs26 \nosupersub \
Hamilton has also experimented with the {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Foilboard"}}{\fldrslt \cf3 foilboard}}, an innovative {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Surfboard"}}{\fldrslt \cf3 surfboard}} which incorporates {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Hydrofoil"}}{\fldrslt \cf3 hydrofoil}} technology allowing a higher degree of precision and effectiveness of aerial techniques within the water.{\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Laird_Hamilton#cite_note-9"}}{\fldrslt 
\fs22 \cf3 [9]}}He has become a proponent of {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Stand_up_paddle_surfing"}}{\fldrslt \cf3 Stand up paddle surfing}}, an {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ancient_Hawaii"}}{\fldrslt \cf3 ancient Hawaiian}} technique that requires a longboard and a long-handled paddle, as well as considerable skill, strength and agility. Purist surfers have blasted him for this, but Hamilton calls it a return to the traditional Hawaiian way of surfing, as practiced by King {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Kamehameha_I"}}{\fldrslt \cf3 Kamehameha I}} and his queen {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Kaahumanu"}}{\fldrslt \cf3 Ka\uc0\u699 ahumanu}} almost three hundred years ago.\
